"""
MKT Context Commentary — 1 Samuel chapters 28–31
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-1samuel-28-31.py

Ch 28: Philistine mobilization; Saul's three-channel failure; séance at Endor.
Ch 29: David dismissed from Philistine muster at Aphek.
Ch 30: Amalekite raid on Ziklag; David's recovery expedition; equal-shares ruling.
Ch 31: Battle of Gilboa; death of Saul and Jonathan; Jabesh-Gilead's faithfulness.

Context focus: ANE necromancy practices, Jezreel Valley geography, Beth-shan archaeology,
Endor location, Philistine military organization, Ziklag's situation, Amalekite raiding patterns,
Jabesh-Gilead's relationship to Benjamin.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(type_, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{type_}' / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(type_, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{type_}' / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, text in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = text

CONTEXT = {
  "28": {
    "1": "<p>The Philistines gather their forces to fight against Israel; Achish informs David that he and his men will join the campaign. David's response — 'you will know what your servant can do' — is deliberately ambiguous: it sounds like commitment but could be interpreted as a statement of capability without specifying for whom. David has spent over a year at Ziklag pretending to raid Judahite towns while actually raiding Amalekites and other southern peoples (27:8-12). His loyalty to Achish is a performance, not a reality.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Achish's appointment of David as his permanent bodyguard is the highest expression of trust from a foreign king — the bodyguard role required absolute physical proximity and covenant loyalty. Achish genuinely believes David has defected from Saul and is now his loyal vassal. The political irony is complete: Israel's future king is about to march as a Philistine officer against the Israelite army containing his predecessor and his best friend.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The narrative resumes its retrospective: Samuel is dead, buried in Ramah, mourned by all Israel. The detail of Samuel's death (introduced in 25:1) is now the crucial backstory for what follows. Saul had expelled the mediums and necromancers (<em>bāʿălê hāʾôḇôṯ wəhayyiddəʿōnîm</em>) earlier in his reign — this expulsion was covenant compliance with the Torah prohibition (Lev 19:31; 20:27; Deut 18:11). Now, with Samuel dead and YHWH silent, Saul faces the ultimate oracular vacuum.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The Philistines encamp at Shunem in the Jezreel Valley; Saul gathers all Israel and encamps at Gilboa. The Jezreel Valley (modern Marj Ibn ʿAmir) is one of the great military corridors of the ancient Near East — it connects the coastal plain to the Jordan Valley, providing flat terrain ideal for chariot warfare. Shunem (modern Sulam) sits on the northern edge of the valley at the foot of the Hill of Moreh. Gilboa (Jebel Fuqūʿa) is the ridge on the south side, where Israel's defensive position would have been elevated but exposed to flanking.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Saul sees the Philistine camp and is afraid — his heart trembles greatly. The terror that seizes Saul reflects genuine strategic danger: the Philistine force was positioned to cut off Israelite territory and the Jezreel corridor. But the theological dimension is equally prominent: Saul's fear is the fear of a man who knows he has been abandoned by YHWH. He has no prophet (Samuel dead), no functioning oracle (Urim removed with the priestly line), and no dreams to rely on.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Saul inquires of YHWH through three channels: dreams, Urim, and prophets. YHWH does not answer through any of them. The three channels represent the three standard modes of divine communication in ancient Israel: nocturnal visions in sleep, the priestly binary oracle of the sacred lots (Urim and Thummim), and prophetic utterance. Saul's exclusion from all three simultaneously signals total divine abandonment. The Urim had already effectively passed to David (Abiathar took the ephod to David in 22:20; 23:6).</p>",
    "7": "<p>Saul instructs his servants to find a woman who is a <em>bāʿalat-ʾôb</em> — a mistress/keeper of a consulting spirit. The <em>ʾôb</em> was a chthonic spirit or ancestral shade that a specialist could invoke to communicate with the dead. Necromancy — consulting the spirits of the deceased for oracular guidance — was widespread in the ancient Near East. Mesopotamian texts describe elaborate rituals for summoning the dead (<em>eṭemmu</em>); Ugaritic texts reference necromantic specialists. The Endor woman is a professional in a technically illegal but apparently still-practiced trade.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Saul disguises himself and goes to Endor at night with two men. Endor (modern Khirbet Safsafeh) is on the north slope of the Hill of Moreh, between Shunem (the Philistine camp) and Gilboa (the Israelite camp) — Saul must pass around or through the Philistine positions to reach it, which explains the night travel. The disguise is pragmatic: the king who expelled all necromancers cannot appear in person at one's door.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The woman's fear when Saul asks her to consult a spirit reflects the genuine legal risk she faces. She has heard of Saul's expulsion decree and fears being caught by royal agents. Her caution — 'why are you laying a trap for my life to bring about my death?' — is the professional's recognition of entrapment tactics. Saul's reassurance ('as YHWH lives, you will have no trouble') is one of the most ironic oaths in the Hebrew Bible: the man who outlawed her practice swears by YHWH to protect her while asking her to do it.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Saul swears by YHWH that no punishment will come to the woman for this act. The oath by YHWH to protect someone while asking them to violate YHWH's law is the theological contradiction at the heart of the scene. Saul's willingness to invoke YHWH's name in the service of necromantic consultation epitomizes the disconnection between his religious language and his theological reality.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The woman asks whom she should bring up; Saul asks for Samuel. The verb <em>heʿĕlāh</em> (bring up) is the standard necromantic term — the dead are in Sheol, beneath; summoning them requires 'bringing up.' The woman's ability to consult Samuel specifically implies that she had a professional method for identifying and summoning particular shades rather than merely general ancestral spirits. Whether the appearance of Samuel represents an actual divine intrusion (YHWH overriding normal practice to confront Saul) or the expected result of her séance is a question the text leaves open.</p>",
    "12": "<p>When the woman sees Samuel, she shrieks and cries out to Saul: 'Why have you deceived me? You are Saul!' The woman's sudden recognition of Saul — coinciding with her vision of Samuel — suggests a connection in her mind between the appearance of the great prophet and the identity of the disguised client. The shriek may express genuine supernatural terror, or it may be the woman's realization that she has performed illegal magic for the king himself.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The woman describes seeing a divine being (<em>ʾĕlōhîm</em>) coming up from the earth. The term <em>ʾĕlōhîm</em> used for Samuel's shade is the same term used for God throughout the Hebrew Bible — in this context it describes the shade as a supernatural being with divine-realm status, not a mere ghost. Ancient Israelite theology located the spirits of the dead in a divine-realm liminal space (Sheol), giving them a quasi-divine categorization distinct from living humans.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Saul asks what the figure looks like; the woman says an old man wrapped in a robe (<em>məʿîl</em>). The robe is the identifying detail — it matches the garment whose corner David cut in ch24, and it is the distinctive garment associated with Samuel's priestly-prophetic role (cf. 2:19; 15:27). Saul bows to the ground — prostrating before the shade of the prophet he repeatedly disobeyed. The posture enacts the submission he refused in life.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Samuel's first words: 'Why have you disturbed me by bringing me up?' The disturbance of the dead was considered a serious transgression in ANE cultures — Mesopotamian texts warn against disturbing ancestral shades. Samuel's irritation is both realistic (within the ANE framework of the dead's rest) and pointed: Saul is trying to obtain from the dead prophet what he could not receive through legitimate means. Samuel's question — 'Why do you ask me, since YHWH has turned from you?' — identifies the real problem: the oracle vacuum is not technical but relational.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Samuel's declaration: 'YHWH has turned from you and become your enemy.' The Hebrew <em>wayəhî rēʿeḵā</em> — 'has become your adversary/enemy' — uses the same root as <em>rāʿāh</em> (evil). YHWH has moved from being Saul's patron to being his opponent. In ANE covenantal theology, the suzerain who was offended by the vassal could move from patron to punisher — the relationship did not end but reversed in valence. Saul's covenant violation has inverted YHWH's posture toward him.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Samuel reconfirms the transfer of the kingdom to David: 'YHWH has done to you as he spoke by me — he has torn the kingdom from your hand and given it to your neighbor David.' The word <em>qāraʿ</em> (torn) is the same word used when Saul's robe was torn in 15:27-28, when Samuel said the kingdom would be torn from him. The tearing-robe acted as a prophetic sign; now Samuel announces its fulfillment.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Samuel identifies the specific reason: Saul did not obey YHWH's voice or execute his burning wrath against Amalek. The Amalek failure of ch15 — the incomplete <em>ḥērem</em> — is the named cause of the dynasty's fall. The connection between the Amalek disobedience and the Jezreel defeat is explicitly made by the shade of Samuel: the incomplete past judgment is now being completed in the present military crisis.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Samuel's final oracle: 'Tomorrow you and your sons shall be with me, and YHWH will give the army of Israel also into the hand of the Philistines.' The death sentence is specific in timing (tomorrow), in scope (Saul and his sons), and in its framing ('with me' in Sheol). The oracle delivers what Saul came for — a word about the battle's outcome — but it is the worst possible word. The séance has succeeded technically and failed completely for Saul.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Saul falls full length on the ground, overwhelmed by fear and by the fact that he has eaten nothing all day and night. The physical collapse enacts his psychological state: there is nothing left. The detail of fasting heightens his physical depletion — already weakened by hunger, the terrifying oracle leaves him prostrate. The woman and Saul's servants must encourage him to eat before he can move.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The woman comes to Saul and sees he is greatly troubled. She urges him to eat, citing that she took her life in her hands to obey him. The domestic scene of a woman preparing bread for the king in the middle of the night — following a séance in which his death was pronounced — is among the most poignant in Samuel. The woman who practiced the forbidden art becomes an unlikely nurse to the dying king.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Saul refuses at first — he has been lying prostrate and will not rise to eat. His refusal may be the paralysis of grief or a last remnant of cultic awareness: eating before a military action could have ritual dimensions. But the servants join the woman in urging him to eat and regain strength for the journey.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The servants join the woman in urging Saul to eat. He listens, rises from the ground, and sits on the bed. The act of rising and sitting is the minimal restoration of functional posture — he is not renewed, not healed, not hopeful; merely upright enough to continue.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The woman slaughters a fattened calf that she has in the house — a significant domestic animal reserved for special occasions — and bakes unleavened bread. The meal she prepares is a final royal feast: fatted calf and fresh bread in the middle of the night for a king who will die the next day. The hospitality is generous and darkly ironic — she honors the man who outlawed her.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The food is set before Saul and his servants; they eat, rise, and leave that same night. The chapter ends in darkness: Saul and his men slip back through the night to their forces at Gilboa, carrying only the knowledge of their imminent deaths. The journey back — through or around the Philistine camp at Shunem — is the condemned man's walk to the place of execution.</p>"
  },
  "29": {
    "1": "<p>The Philistine forces are assembled at Aphek — the same site where the battle that captured the ark occurred (ch4). The Jezreel spring (Ein Harod) provides water at the base of Gilboa for the Israelite camp. Aphek as staging ground is a deliberate narrative geography: the book that began with Israelite defeat at Aphek will end with another Israelite defeat at Gilboa, this time definitively ending the Saulide period. The Philistine muster at Aphek frames the book's military arc.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The Philistine lords march with their contingents of hundreds and thousands; David and his men march at the rear with Achish. The Philistine military organization by hundreds and thousands reflects a decimal system consistent with both the Israelite tribal levy and ANE army administrative structures. David's position at the rear — with his own patron's unit — is the position of a vassal contingent, attached to but not fully integrated into the main Philistine force.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The Philistine commanders ask: 'What are these Hebrews doing here?' The term <em>ʿiḇrîm</em> (Hebrews) carries its characteristic outsider-distancing connotation — not 'Israelites' but the generic term for the semi-nomadic mercenary class. The commanders' objection is militarily prudent: Hebrews fighting as mercenaries for the Philistines had a well-known pattern of switching sides. Egyptian records from the New Kingdom period document <em>ʿApiru</em> (a cognate term) mercenaries who proved unreliable.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The Philistine commanders insist David be sent back to Ziklag. Their concern — 'he might become an adversary in the battle' (<em>śāṭān</em>) — uses the term that will later develop into a title for the divine accuser. The commanders' fear is that David might 'reconcile himself to his lord' — defect to Saul — by offering Israelite heads during battle. The phrase 'the heads of those men' is the price of reconciliation in ANE diplomatic practice.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The commanders cite the victory song: 'Saul has struck his thousands, and David his ten thousands.' The fact that the Philistine commanders know this specific chant confirms what was noted in 21:11 — David's reputation and the details of his reception in Israel were known throughout the region. The song is evidence that David was never fully a Philistine vassal in the commanders' eyes; his Israelite celebrity was too well-established.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Achish calls David and says: 'As YHWH lives, you have been trustworthy.' Achish invokes YHWH — not Dagon or Baal — when speaking to David, either as a courtesy using David's deity or because YHWH's name was recognized as the reliable divine guarantor in this cultural context. His assessment of David as 'good in my sight as a messenger of God' uses divine-agent language — the highest endorsement a Philistine king could offer.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Achish instructs David to return to Ziklag in peace, doing nothing that is evil in the sight of the Philistine lords. The pragmatic deference to the other lords' judgment is the political reality of the pentapolis system: Achish cannot override the collective decision of the five lords. His personal vouching for David is insufficient against their structural objection.</p>",
    "8": "<p>David protests: 'What have I done? What have you found in your servant from the day I entered your service until now, that I may not go and fight against the enemies of my lord the king?' The protest is strategically ambiguous — 'my lord the king' could refer to Achish or to YHWH's anointed king (David himself, or even Saul). The protest maintains the mercenary fiction while creating a plausible exit.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Achish repeats his endorsement and his inability to override the other lords. The political structure of the Philistine pentapolis — five co-equal city-states with collective veto capacity — creates the structural pressure that extricates David from having to fight against Israel. The Philistine commanders have unknowingly acted as YHWH's instruments by removing David from a position that would have forced a catastrophic choice.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Achish instructs David and his men to depart early in the morning. The urgency of the early departure reflects the commanders' desire to have the Hebrew contingent gone before the battle; a presence that creates suspicion in the ranks is a liability even if idle. David and his men set out to return to the land of the Philistines — Ziklag — while the Philistines go up to Jezreel.</p>",
    "11": "<p>David and his men rise early and travel back through the Philistine territory. The narrative juxtaposition is stark: as David heads south to Ziklag, the Philistine army moves north to Jezreel where Saul and Jonathan will die. David's absence from Gilboa is providential — he is spared having to fight against his covenant people and is positioned to respond appropriately to the news of the disaster when it comes (2 Sam 1:1-12).</p>"
  },
  "30": {
    "1": "<p>David and his men arrive at Ziklag on the third day to find it burned — the Amalekites have raided while the men were away with the Philistine muster. Ziklag (possibly Tell esh-Shariya/Tel Sera) was on the southern frontier of Judahite territory, in the Negev — exposed to raids from the south and east. The Amalekites operated in the same southern desert regions David had been raiding (27:8-12). The raid is a strategic counter-response: while David raided Amalekite territory, they struck his home base in his absence.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The Amalekites did not kill anyone but took everyone captive — women and children from young to old. The selective taking of captives without killing reflects the economic logic of slave raiding in the ancient Near East: living captives were worth substantially more than corpses, both for ransom and for sale into slavery. The Amalekite raiders were conducting a profitable abduction operation, not a vendetta.</p>",
    "3": "<p>David and his men come to the city — it is burned and their wives and sons and daughters have been taken captive. The full scope of the disaster: every family in the entire Ziklag garrison has been taken. The 600 men David commanded (23:13) are all simultaneously bereaved of their families. The communal catastrophe creates the conditions for the communal grief and near-mutiny of v4-6.</p>",
    "4": "<p>David and the people weep until there is no more strength in them to weep. The complete exhaustion of grief — weeping until physically unable to continue — is a psychologically precise description of acute communal trauma. The men have marched for three days from Aphek, arrived to destroyed homes, and now mourn while too exhausted to act.</p>",
    "5": "<p>David's two wives — Ahinoam of Jezreel and Abigail the widow of Nabal of Carmel — have also been taken. The personal dimension of the raid intersects with the communal: David has lost not just his men's families but his own household. His leadership role requires him to lead while personally mourning the same loss as his men.</p>",
    "6": "<p>David is in great distress because the people speak of stoning him — each man is bitter in soul for his sons and daughters. The near-mutiny is the logical outcome of 600 men simultaneously blaming their leader for the disaster. David's decision to bring them on the Philistine muster created the tactical opportunity for the raid. David's response: he strengthens himself in YHWH his God (<em>wayyitḥazzēq dāwîḏ baYHWH ʾĕlōhāyw</em>). This is the first explicit reference to David's personal spiritual resource in extremity — the source of his resilience is theological, not merely psychological.</p>",
    "7": "<p>David inquires of YHWH through Abiathar and the ephod: 'Shall I pursue this raiding party? Shall I overtake them?' YHWH answers: 'Pursue, for you shall surely overtake and shall surely rescue.' The ephod consultation in crisis is David's consistent pattern (23:2,4,9-12). The oracle is unambiguous and confident — the unusual double infinitive absolute (<em>nāḵôn tassîg wəhassēl tassîl</em>) emphasizes certainty. David acts immediately on the oracle.</p>",
    "8": "<p>David sets out with the 600 men and comes to the Wadi Besor. The Besor is a seasonal stream in the northern Negev (modern Nahal Besor) approximately 25 km south of Ziklag. Its significance is as a major obstacle in the southern Negev — its steep banks and the exhaustion of the men make it a natural stopping point for those who cannot continue.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Two hundred men are too exhausted to cross the Besor and stay behind; the remaining 400 continue the pursuit. The exhaustion of a third of the force after the three-day march from Aphek plus the emotional trauma of Ziklag's destruction is physiologically realistic. The 400 who continue are those with reserves sufficient to sustain the pursuit; the 200 who stay are not cowards but men at their physical limit.</p>",
    "10": "<p>David goes on with 400 men. The division of forces and the subsequent controversy about spoil-sharing (v21-25) establishes the specific military administrative question that David's ruling will address. The narrative preserves the exact numbers because they matter for the legal precedent.</p>",
    "11": "<p>They find an Egyptian in the field and bring him to David. He is given bread to eat and water to drink — the provision of food and water before questioning follows the ANE practice of establishing hospitality obligations before interrogating. A man who has received food and water is under the household's protection and is expected to respond faithfully to questions.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The Egyptian is fed — figs, raisins, water — and his spirit revives after three days without food. He is an Amalekite slave who had been abandoned when he became sick during the raid. The abandoned slave is YHWH's providential guide: the one discarded by the enemy becomes the one who leads David to them. The pattern of the enemy's cast-off becoming the instrument of their defeat recurs throughout biblical narrative.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The Egyptian is a servant of an Amalekite. His master left him behind when he fell ill three days ago. The three-day gap between the Amalekite departure and David's arrival means the raiding party is at most three days' travel ahead — still catchable if the 400 can close the distance quickly. The Egyptian knows the route and the destination.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The Egyptian confirms the scope of the raid: they struck the Negev of the Cherethites, of Judah, and of Caleb, and burned Ziklag with fire. The Cherethites are the Aegean-origin peoples settled in the southern coastal plain (cognate with Cretans — Philistine-related peoples). The geographic spread of the raid — Cherethite, Judahite, Calebite territory — indicates an opportunistic wide-ranging operation, not a targeted strike on Ziklag alone.</p>",
    "15": "<p>David asks him to lead them to the raiding party; the Egyptian requests a sworn guarantee of life and non-extradition to his master. The swearing of protection (<em>hiššābaʿ lî bēʾlōhîm</em>) before information-giving is a formal legal arrangement — the guide is requesting asylum before acting as informant. David swears, the Egyptian leads.</p>",
    "16": "<p>They arrive to find the Amalekites scattered across the land — eating, drinking, and celebrating over the great plunder from Philistia and Judah. The victory feast of the raiders, spread across the landscape, makes them vulnerable: no defensive formation, no scouts posted, no anticipation of pursuit at this distance. The Amalekites' confidence in their escape has become their tactical undoing.</p>",
    "17": "<p>David strikes them from dusk until the evening of the next day — a continuous battle lasting approximately 24 hours. Only 400 men escape on camels. The use of camels for flight reflects the desert-raiding culture of the Amalekites and related groups — camels provided rapid long-distance escape through terrain impassable for infantry. The escape of 400 on camels means the raiding force was substantially larger than 400 total.</p>",
    "18": "<p>David recovers everything the Amalekites had taken, including his two wives. The full recovery — nothing lost — fulfills the oracle's promise ('you shall surely rescue'). The narrative notes the completeness of the recovery before dealing with the spoil-controversy, establishing that David's leadership has been vindicated before the internal conflict is addressed.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Nothing is missing — small or great, sons or daughters, spoil or anything that had been taken — David brings it all back. The totality of the recovery is emphasized by the fourfold enumeration (small/great, sons/daughters, spoil/whatever taken). The oracle's double certainty ('surely overtake, surely rescue') has been fulfilled in every particular.</p>",
    "20": "<p>David also takes all the flocks and herds, which were driven before the other livestock. The spoil of the Amalekite raid — beyond the recovered captives — includes substantial animal wealth from their original plundering of multiple territories. 'This is David's spoil' — the attribution of the entire recovered wealth to David personally sets up the administrative question of distribution.</p>",
    "21": "<p>David returns to the 200 men who were too exhausted to cross the Besor. They come to meet David and the people; David greets them warmly. The greeting — <em>wayyišʾal lāhem lĕšālôm</em>, he inquired of their wellbeing — is the formal greeting that treats the 200 as valued members of the group, not as failures who stayed behind.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The wicked and worthless men (<em>ʾanšê hārāʿ wəhabbəlîyyaʿal</em>) among the 400 say the 200 who stayed behind should receive only their wives and children and not share in the spoil. The objection has military-legal precedent: in many ancient armies, spoil was distributed only to those who fought. The counter-position David will articulate (v23-24) is a new ruling that establishes a different standard for Israel.</p>",
    "23": "<p>David replies: 'You shall not do so, my brothers, with what YHWH has given us. He has preserved us and given into our hand the raiding party that came against us.' David's argument is theological before it is legal: the victory belongs to YHWH, not to the 400 fighters. If YHWH gave the victory, the distribution belongs to YHWH's community — including those who guarded the baggage.</p>",
    "24": "<p>'Who would listen to you in this matter? For as his share is who goes down into the battle, so shall his share be who stays by the baggage. They shall share alike.' The ruling — equal shares for fighters and logistics personnel — became a standing legal principle in Israel. The same principle appears in the Talmud's rules about spoil distribution. David is not making a charitable exception but establishing a legal precedent that recognizes all contributions to a military operation.</p>",
    "25": "<p>David makes this a statute and ordinance for Israel from that day forward to this day. The legal formula — <em>ḥōq ûmišpāṭ</em> (statute and ordinance) — is the same language used for Torah regulations. David's ruling at Ziklag is his first legislative act as proto-king; he governs before he is formally installed. The Ziklag spoil-ruling is one of the foundations of Israelite military law.</p>",
    "26": "<p>David sends portions of the spoil to the elders of Judah, his friends, with the message: 'Here is a gift for you from the spoil of the enemies of YHWH.' The distribution to Judahite towns is political capital-building before the formal throne bid: David is cultivating relationships with the tribal leadership throughout Judah by sharing recovered spoil from common enemies. The list of towns in vv27-31 covers the Negev and southern Judah — precisely the region he will be declared king of first (2 Sam 2:4).</p>",
    "27": "<p>The first towns listed — Bethel, Ramoth-Negev, Jattir — are in the southern hill country and Negev of Judah. These towns represent communities that had suffered from the same Amalekite raiding that struck Ziklag (v14 identified the Negev of Judah as part of the raid). David is restoring what was taken from these communities while simultaneously demonstrating largesse.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Aroer, Siphmoth, Eshtemoa — additional towns in the southern Judah/Negev region, including Eshtemoa which later appears as a Levitical city (Josh 21:14). The distribution covers a wide geographic footprint, suggesting David's network of relationships in Judah extended throughout the region even during his time at Ziklag.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The distribution reaches Racal, the cities of the Jerahmeelites, and the cities of the Kenites. The Jerahmeelites and Kenites were non-Israelite groups living within Judahite territory — their inclusion in the spoil distribution reflects David's inclusive approach to building political relationships across ethnic boundaries, consistent with his later inclusive policies as king.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Hormah, Bor-ashan, Athach — towns in the far south. Hormah has historical resonance: it was the site of early Israelite military defeats (Num 14:45; 21:3) and later victories. Including it in the distribution honors the full extent of Judahite identity.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Hebron and all the places where David and his men had roamed. Hebron receives the last mention — it will become David's first capital (2 Sam 2:1-4). The summary 'all the places where David and his men had roamed' acknowledges that David's fugitive years had built relationships across the southern highlands that will now support his kingship. The wandering that looked like exile was actually network-building for the kingdom to come.</p>"
  },
  "31": {
    "1": "<p>The Philistines fight Israel; the men of Israel flee before the Philistines and fall slain on Mount Gilboa. The Battle of Gilboa (modern Jebel Fuqūʿa, the ridge on the south side of the Jezreel Valley) was one of the most decisive military disasters in Israelite history. The Jezreel Valley provided the flat terrain where Philistine chariot forces had overwhelming tactical advantage against Israelite infantry on foot. The Israelite position on Gilboa — elevated but exposed and outnumbered — offered no favorable defensive options against a coordinated assault.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The Philistines overtake Saul and his sons; Jonathan, Abinadab, and Malchishua die. Jonathan's death here — in the same battle David was prevented from fighting in (ch29) — is the covenant friend's end. Jonathan, who had consistently acknowledged David's future kingship, dies protecting his father's doomed kingdom. The narrative has nothing more to say about Jonathan; his covenant with David remains enacted in 2 Sam 9's treatment of Mephibosheth.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The battle goes hard against Saul. The archers find him and he is critically wounded. The Philistine archers — the ranged-weapons specialists who could engage from outside hand-combat range — are what ultimately breaks Saul's position. Whether Saul's wounds are from arrows in flight or from archers who had closed to short range, the effect is that the king is incapacitated before a decisive hand-to-hand encounter.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Saul asks his armor-bearer to run him through — 'lest these uncircumcised come and abuse me.' The concern for posthumous bodily violation was widespread in the ancient world: desecrating the enemy king's body was a way of continuing the military humiliation beyond death. Saul's request is the honor-death of a warrior who will not allow his enemies the satisfaction of killing and desecrating him. The armor-bearer is unwilling to strike YHWH's anointed — even at his own king's request — and Saul falls on his own sword.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The armor-bearer, seeing Saul dead, also falls on his sword and dies with him. The death of the armor-bearer following his king is the ANE loyalty custom of the faithful retainer — documented in Mesopotamian burial practices and in the practice of servants being entombed with their masters. The armor-bearer's refusal to kill Saul was covenant reverence; his suicide at Saul's death was covenant loyalty of a different kind.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Saul and his three sons and his armor-bearer and all his men die together that day. The summary is comprehensive: the royal household and its immediate military support are eliminated in a single engagement. This is the fulfillment of Samuel's Endor oracle (28:19: 'tomorrow you and your sons will be with me'). The timing — 'that day' — confirms the oracle's precision.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The men of Israel on the other side of the valley and beyond the Jordan see that Israel's men fled and Saul and his sons are dead — they abandon the cities and flee. The Philistines come and live in them. The collapse of the Israelite military position triggers a regional population flight — settlements that had been under Israelite administration become Philistine-occupied. The scale of the territorial loss sets the context for David's kingship challenge: he inherits a kingdom with a significant Philistine presence in the central valley.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The next day, the Philistines come to strip the dead and find Saul and his three sons fallen on Mount Gilboa. Stripping the battlefield dead was standard post-battle practice across the ancient Near East — equipment, weapons, jewelry, and clothing were all valuable military spoil. The specific finding of the royal bodies transformed what would have been routine plunder into a significant political-religious statement.</p>",
    "9": "<p>They cut off Saul's head and strip his armor, sending word throughout the land of the Philistines and to the temples of their idols. Saul's head is displayed in the temple of Dagon (1 Chr 10:10); his armor is put in the temple of Ashtaroth. The division of the trophy between two temples reflects the Philistine polytheistic practice of distributing victory honors across the pantheon. Beth-shan (modern Tell el-Husn, adjacent to Tell Beth She'an) was a major temple city with excavated temples consistent with this period.</p>",
    "10": "<p>They fasten his body to the wall of Beth-shan. Archaeological excavations at Tell Beth She'an have uncovered massive temple complexes from the Iron Age I period — the site was a major Egyptian administrative center in the Late Bronze Age and continued as a significant city in the early Iron Age. The wall-display of Saul's body at Beth-shan is both a military trophy and a religious statement: YHWH's anointed is displayed at a Philistine religious center as evidence of Philistine divine victory over the God of Israel.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The inhabitants of Jabesh-Gilead hear what the Philistines did to Saul. Jabesh-Gilead's response is immediate and courageous. The relationship between Jabesh-Gilead and Saul began in ch11 where Saul's Spirit-empowered rescue of Jabesh-Gilead from the Ammonite siege was his first royal act. The city had been saved by Saul; now they repay the debt by recovering his body at significant personal risk — Beth-shan was in Philistine-controlled territory.</p>",
    "12": "<p>All the valiant men of Jabesh-Gilead rise and travel through the night, take the bodies of Saul and his sons from the wall of Beth-shan, and bring them to Jabesh. The distance from Jabesh-Gilead (Tell Abu Kharaz in Transjordan) to Beth-shan is approximately 20-25 km — a significant night march across the Jordan and through hostile territory. The 'valiant men' (<em>ʾanšê ḥayil</em>) who undertake this mission risk their lives out of covenant loyalty to the king who delivered them.</p>",
    "13": "<p>They burn the bodies at Jabesh and bury the bones under the tamarisk tree in Jabesh, fasting for seven days. The burning of the bodies was unusual in Israelite practice — normally bodies were buried intact. The burning may have been necessitated by the advanced decomposition of bodies exposed on a wall, or it may reflect a practice associated with royal cremation. The tamarisk tree (<em>ʾešel</em>) is the same species under which Saul held court at Gibeah (22:6) and under which he was eventually reburied (1 Chr 10:12). The seven-day fast is the full mourning period, honoring the king who delivered Jabesh-Gilead in his first act of kingship.</p>"
  }
}

